.TH LPF-EBPF 8 "June 2026" "lpf 0.1.1" "lpf Manual"
.SH NAME
lpf\-ebpf \- compile policy to native eBPF/XDP C source
.SH SYNOPSIS
lpf ebpf [\-\-static] [\-\-map\-updates] <policy>
.SH DESCRIPTION
Compile a policy to a native eBPF/XDP C source file or dynamic map updates.
This generates an XDP program that unifies routing and firewalling at the lowest level.
The default mode generates a generic engine C file. Use \-\-static for a specialized unrolled C file.
Use \-\-map\-updates to generate bpftool commands for populating dynamic maps.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\-\-static
generate specialized C code with rules baked in for maximum performance
.TP
\-\-map\-updates
generate bpftool commands to update dynamic rule maps
.SH EXAMPLES
lpf ebpf /etc/lpf.conf > lpf_xdp.c
lpf ebpf \-\-static /etc/lpf.conf > lpf_xdp_static.c
lpf ebpf \-\-map\-updates /etc/lpf.conf | sh
clang \-O2 \-target bpf \-c lpf_xdp.c \-o lpf_xdp.o
.SH FILES
/etc/lpf.conf
/var/lib/lpf/history
/var/lib/lpf/rollback
.SH SAFETY NOTES
This command is read\-only. Compiling and attaching the eBPF object is done separately.
.SH EXIT STATUS
0 on success.
Non\-zero when validation, planning, or host operations fail.
.SH SEE ALSO
lpf\-plan(8), lpf\-rules(8)
